SIMPLE: saunter
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saunter
<hw>Saun"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sauntered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sauntering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Written also
<ets>santer</ets>.]</ety> <ety>[Probably fr. F. <ets>s'aventurer</ets>
to adventure (one's self), through a shortened form
<ets>s'auntrer</ets>. See <er>Adventure</er>, <pos>n. & v.</pos>]</ety>
<def>To wander or walk about idly and in a leisurely or lazy manner; to
lounge; to stroll; to loiter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One could lie under elm trees in a lawn, or <qex>saunter</qex> in
meadows by the side of a stream.</q> <rj><qau>Masson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To loiter; linger; stroll; wander.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saunter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Saunter
<hw>Saun"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sauntering, or a sauntering
place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That wheel of fops, that <qex>saunter</qex> of the town.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saunterer</ent>⟦br⟧
